[2] Cholera - Tanzania (Dar es Salaam and Morogoro regions)
Date: Fri 28 Aug 2015
Source: Voice of America (VOA) [edited]
http://www.voanews.com/content/world-health-organization-who-tanzania-cholera-epidemic/2936285.html


The World Health Organization and the Tanzanian Ministry of Health are stepping up efforts to contain and discover the source of a cholera epidemic that so far has killed 8 people and infected more than 400 others.

WHO data indicates that the fast-spreading epidemic broke out in the Dar es Salaam and Morogoro regions nearly 2 weeks ago; the Dar es Salaam region has been most adversely affected with 354 cases and 7 deaths.

WHO spokesman Christian Lindmeier tells VOA the outbreak caught health officials by surprise. "The spike is an unusual spike right now because it jumped in short time from a few hundred cases to the 404 cases," he said. "Yet cholera is endemic in Tanzania, so, as such, it is not a worrying situation, but it needs to be addressed."

After assessing needs on the ground in affected areas, WHO officials have begun procuring laboratory reagents for diagnosis. Lindmeier also says the agency is outfitting 5 operational treatment centers in the affected region with medical supplies and chemicals to treat water and disinfectants. WHO officials have said they see no connection between the current outbreak and a prior, more serious outbreak in western Tanzania's Kigoma region, which borders portions of Lake Tanganyika and Burundi.

"The cholera outbreak in Kigoma region reported between May and July [2015], related to the refugees coming from Burundi at that time, has been brought under control, with no new cases from that area for nearly a month," Lindmeier said.

The epidemic among refugees resulted in more than 4800 cases and claimed dozens of lives.

[Byline: Lisa Schlein]

