[3] Cholera - South Sudan (Central Equatoria and Jonglei States)
Date: Sun 16 Aug 2015 [note date]
Source: ReliefWeb [edited]
http://reliefweb.int/report/south-sudan/situation-report-56-cholera-south-sudan-2359-hours-16-august-2015


As of 16 Aug 2015, a total of 1600 cholera cases including 45 deaths (CFR 2.8 percent) have been reported in Juba and Bor Counties in Central Equatoria and Jonglei States.

In Juba County, 1470 cases including 44 deaths (CFR 2.99 percent) have been reported. In Bor, 130 cases including one death (CFR 0.77 percent) have been reported from Malou in Makuach Payam and other areas within the county. Kator, Rejaf, Northern Bari, Gondokoro, and Munuki are the most affected areas in Juba County, with attack rates (cases per 10 000) of 252, 221, 167, 26.7, and 26.6, respectively. Makuach is the most affected area in Bor and has registered an attack rate (cases per 10 000) of 33.

A total of 18 new cholera cases were reported in Juba on 16 Aug 2015 with the majority originating from Gondokoro, Jebel Dinka, and Gumbo Shirkat. During week 33 of 2015 (week of 16 Aug 2015), most of the cholera cases in Juba originated from Gondokoro; Gurei, Lemon Gaba, and Mangatain, Jebel Dinka, and Gudele in Northern Bari; Gumbo in Rejaf; Nyakuron and Jebel Kujur in Munuki; Kor William in Kator; and Buluk and Tongping in Juba (Figures 1.1 and 3). During week 33 of 2015, the most affected areas in Juba County were Gondokoro, Northern Bari, Kator, Rejaf, Munuki, and Juba, which registered attack rates (cases per 10 000) of 15.5, 14.5, 8.8, 7.0, 1.2, and 0.9 respectively.

Within Juba County and its most affected areas of Juba, Northern Bari, Munuki, Rejaf, and Kator, children under 10 years and young adults aged 20-34 years are the most affected, while in Makuach, Bor County, children under 10 years are the most affected. Out of the 1464 cholera cases with known gender in Juba, 637 (44 percent) were female, while 827 (56 percent) were male, while in Bor, 75 (58 percent) of the cases were females, while 55 (42 percent) were males.

The probable risk factors fueling transmission include: residing in a crowded IDP camp with poor sanitation and hygiene; using untreated water from the water tankers; lack of household chlorination of drinking water; eating food from unregulated roadside food vendors or makeshift markets; open defecation/poor latrine use; and attending/eating food at a funeral.

A total of 324 (90 percent) of the samples have been RDT positive, while 46 (41 percent) have been confirmed by culture after the National Public Health Laboratory isolated _Vibrio cholerae_ O1 Inaba. Most of the culture-confirmed cases have been reported from Juba.

Seven stool samples were shipped to the Central Public Health Laboratory in Uganda for testing. _Vibrio cholerae_ O1 serogroup Inaba was isolated from one of the samples, while 6 samples tested negative for cholera but were positive for nonpathogenic _Escherichia coli_. Three isolates were confirmed as positive, and 3 tested negative on repeat testing in Uganda, thus confirming earlier test results by the National Public Health Laboratory.

